2} <U+2601><U+FE0F>Know The Weather<U+2601><U+FE0F>
-This goes with the first tip. Before you start packing make sure you check the weather so you know what kind of clothing to bring! For a more accurate result maybe try calling up a friend or family member and ask them how the weather is like!

3} <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B3><U+00B1>Car Occupation<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B3><U+00B1>
-Obviously on a road trip, you are going to have a whole until you get to your hotel or destination. So you want to make sure you pack something to do in the car. Here are some suggestions. -phone, obviously!
-iPod
-headphones
-book
-download movies/music
-snacks

4}<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B3><U+00B7>Record The Memories<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B3><U+00B9>
-Make sure you bring a camera and capture all the memories! Never forget the fun times!

5}<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+008C>Coziness<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+008C>
-Make sure you bring a pillow and blanket so that in the car you can sleep with comfort! Also make sure you wear comfy clothing.

6} <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+009C>Over/Under Packing<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+009C>
-Make sure you plan your outfits for each day! You never want to bring to much or not bring enough!

In this day in age alot of people have taken up photography, including myself. And I see it more and more that as the art form expands it just gets more boring and bland. Here's a shot of @deadreak hanging out on Matthes Crest. He and I took a quick trip from #SF out to Yosemite so he could show me another beautiful climbing route with awesome mountaineering type scrambling at the top. The crest is about a mile long granite fin and is 10,923 feet in elevation. The route itself is 500 feet high. Matthes Crest is part of the Cathedral Range which is found inside of #yosemitenationalpark, part of the stunning Sierra Nevada. It's named after François Matthes, a cartographer and author who described the geology of the region. Do you love nature and the outdoors? Over the course of my readings, I had learned that the human eye is more sophisticated than any camera of similar size. The cells on the outer layer of the retina can absorb a single particle of light, or photon, and amplify its energy at least a million times, before transferring it in the form of a nervous signal to the back of the brain. The iris, which functions as the eye’s diaphragm, is automatically controlled. The cornea has just the right curvature. The lens is focused by miniature muscles, which are also controlled automatically by feedback. The final result of this visual system, still imperfectly understood in its entirety, is a clear, colored, and three-dimensional image inside the brain that we perceive as external. We never see reality, but only an internal representation of it that our brain constructs for us continuously. [Jeremy Narby, The Cosmic Serpent] // what does the world look like inside your brain? #followyouradventure // pc: @zapote

They giggled and laughed in the very early morning knowing how wonderful it is to be in each others arms.

#susa #castle , #khuzestan , #Iran .

Located in the south-west of Iran, in the lower Zagros Mountains, the property encompasses a group of archaeological mounds rising on the eastern side of the Shavur #River, as well as Ardeshir’s palace, on the opposite bank of the river. The excavated architectural monuments include administrative, residential and palatial structures. Susa contains several layers of superimposed urban settlements in a continuous succession from the late 5th millennium BCE until the 13thcentury CE. The #site bears exceptional testimony to the Elamite, #Persian and Parthian #cultural traditions, which have largely disappeared.

Such an awesome atmosphere! Then we walked to Piccadilly Circus, then on to Oxford Street, Tottenham Court Road and back to our hostel! This piece is titled "Learning Confuses" it is just under four feet tall and is made from stoneware. It has been bisqued to come 2 and acrylic paints and mediums have been applied to the surface. The form is an undulating tangle of concave and convex areas, much like the idea of how learning confuses us. caption: Day 9: a part of our group stayed to finish the work on buildings' remains, while the other went on wondering around the area. We wondered our bus into a ditch and it took 2 tractors to get it out. All day brought pretty much nothing, but the last stop at one of the fields, which smelled horrible thanks to a neighboring farm, gave interesting results: a pithos (big container jar) and pieces of ceramics datable to 3,000-2,000 BC (Bronze Age), Hellenistic and Roman periods.
